  <span id="freeText7365865919172370681" style="display:none">I first thought this was going to be just a usual missing-person thriller, but it turned out to be something else.<br /><br />Of course, this might be a smart trick of the author or the person who wrote the cover notes: with the blurb and first chapter they arouse the interest of readers like me, who are in the mood for reading a missing-person thriller, but then, when I'm already in the story anyway, the story moves on in a completely different direction - one that happens to be much more interesting than a regular missing-person story.<br /><br />Because the dead body of a child, discovered at the beginning of the story in a Kansas field, is just an excuse - an excuse to bring back the drug addict prodigal son from the far-away city to his ailing mother, who is maniacally interested in the fate of missing children; an excuse for the mother to tell the most important story of her life in multiple versions, to multiple people; another chance to discover, remember, or make up the one true story of a life.<br /><br />In any case - this novel is slower, more melancholy, and more lyrical than I would have thought.<br /><br />And what's especially good is that Heim doesn't use any of the usual postmodern tricks to mix reality and fiction in his book - this novel can be read <i>as a novel</i>, but it's not too difficult to notice the similarities to the real life of the real author, either. But Heim, manifesting wonderful self-discipline or perhaps wisdom, doesn't emphasize this ambiguity. Why emphasize, anyway, that it's impossible to know the truth about a life, and that even the story of a single life can be wildly different, depending on who tells it to whom - it's all obvious. And Heim has this gift: not to emphasize the obvious, just making you feel it.</span>
