  <span id="freeText7140602017426950481" style="display:none">This story of a mother and son is one of those "is it or isn't it?" stories of crypto-autobiography, in which the author names the main character after himself and inserts certain factual elements of his life, but leaves readers scratching their heads over what elements of the story are truth or fiction.<br /><br />I was excited to see a new Scott Heim book had been published, since I was a fan of his first novel and it's been years since he's cranked out anything new. Because of this, I was patient with his decision to insert a literary doppelganger into his novel, especially since the story seemed to be his way of coming to terms with his (real) mother's death.<br /><br />Patience is the key word for readers of this book, which concerns itself with a mystery involving the abduction of Scott's mother when she was a child, and her revelation of those events during the last days of her life. I found the "mystery" aspect of this book fairly tedious and unrewarding, but the account of Scott's relationship with his mother during her dying days made the less interesting aspects of the book at least tolerable.<br /><br />Certainly the story Heim created of his mother's childhood abduction makes perfect sense to him and serves as a fitting metaphor, whether the rest of the world needs to be in on the connection or not. For me, the suspense/mystery aspect of the book weighed down what could otherwise have been a very powerful and touching character study, and a painfully insightful tale of loss.<br /><br />If you enjoyed "Mysterious Skin" and "In Awe", by all means you'll find a familiar voice in this book. If you're unfamiliar with Heim's work, this is not the introduction for you.</span>
